REASONS FOR JUDGMENT

CURRAN J:

INTRODUCTION

This is an application for final parenting orders between the applicant mother, Ms Bonhomme (“the mother”) and the respondent father, Mr Bonhomme (“the father”) in respect of X (currently six years of age) and Y (currently four years of age).
During the trial, orders were made by consent resolving a number of parenting orders that had previously been in dispute. Having been satisfied that the orders proposed were in the best interests of the children, they were made on 26 November 2025.
The remaining issues in dispute concerned parental responsibility, the time the children will spend with their father, which school the children will attend and several ancillary issues.
In respect of parental responsibility, the mother sought orders for sole decision-making responsibility while the father sought orders for joint decision-making responsibility.
The mother had unilaterally changed the residence of the children from the Suburb B area to the City H area, but by the time of the final trial, there was no dispute that the children would continue to live with their mother in the City H area and spend time with their father in the Suburb B area. There were no issues of risk. There was no dispute that both parties had the capacity to meet the developmental, emotional, psychological and cultural needs of the children in their respective households.
The parties each sought orders for the children to spend significant time with their father with whom they have a close and loving relationship. The mother sought an arrangement where the children would spend four nights each fortnight with their father in 2026 during the school terms, transitioning to five nights each fortnight during terms in 2027, and time increasing to half school holidays. The father sought orders for five nights per fortnight in 2026, transitioning to six nights each fortnight in 2027 during term and half holidays.
The parties remained in dispute about which school the children should attend. The father gave evidence that he considered the travel burden on the children if they attended the school preferred by the mother would be too great, such that if an order was made for the children to attend the mother’s preferred school, his time with the children would, by necessity, not increase.
The question of what time with the father is in the best interests of the children is informed by considering each of the matters set out in s 60CC of the Family Law Act 1975 (Cth) (“the Act”). In this case, given the distance between the parties respective homes, the benefit of the children having a relationship with each parent is also informed by a consideration of time arrangements that can practically be implemented.

BACKGROUND

The father is 45 years of age, and the mother is 36 years of age. Cohabitation commenced in 2012 or 2013. They married in 2016 and separated on a final basis on 13 September 2023, the same day the mother commenced parenting proceedings.
The mother commenced a romantic relationship with Mr G in around May 2023. They reside together and Mr G’s two children are in a shared time arrangement with their respective mothers. The mother and Mr G are currently engaged.
Following separation, the father remained and continues to live in the former matrimonial home.
The mother and children resided in a friend’s home in Region BB prior to residing with the mother’s grandmother in Suburb J. By August 2024, she and the children were spending up to six nights a fortnight in the City H area with Mr G.
Interim orders were made on 24 October 2024 by Senior Judicial Registrar Turner for the children to live with the mother and spend increasing time with the father on an unsupervised and overnight basis; for X to be enrolled in D School in 2025; and for Y to continue schooling at E Early Learning Centre from Monday to Thursday in 2025. No orders were made as to where the mother was to live. The practical effect of these circumstances was that the children travelled between their school in Suburb B and the mother’s various residences in the City H area for approximately 18 months. The interim orders remained in force at the date of the trial.
The mother filed an Application for Review on 28 November 2024 which was dismissed by McGuire J on 12 December 2024. The mother appealed this decision which was dismissed by the Full Court.
Notwithstanding the interim orders, the mother again relocated with the children without notice to Suburb CC in on 20 December 2024, further away from Sydney due to Mr G’s lease ending at Suburb K.
On 2 October 2025, the mother once again relocated with the children without notice to Suburb AA, to a home she had purchased, which was again a move further away from Sydney.
The practical effect of these circumstances has required the children to travel a long distance between their school in Suburb B and the mother’s residence in Suburb AA.
Prior to the mother’s unilateral relocation, the parties had agreed that the children would receive a private education such that the children were to attend M School from Year 3. The mother sought orders for the children to attend F School (being the school the youngest of Mr G’s daughters attends) and the father sought orders that the children attend U School, a school approximately midway between the parties’ respective homes.

ISSUES IN DISPUTE

By the end of the trial, the remaining issues for determination became:
(a) What long-term decision-making orders are in the children’s best interests;

(b) What orders for time with the father are in the children’s best interests;

(c) Whether the children should attend school at U School or F School;

(d) What the configuration of the long school holiday regime should be;

(e) Whether there should be a mutual first option to care if the parent (and their partner if applicable) is unable to care for longer than 48 hours;

(f) Whether overseas travel should be permitted immediately or only after Term 4 2027;

(g) The terms of restraints each party sought to be made; and

(h) Whether the parents should be ordered to continue their mental health treatment.

MATERIAL RELIED ON

The mother relied upon the following documents at the final hearing as set out in her Case Outline:
(a) Further Further Further Further Amended Initiating Application filed 10 October 2025;

(b) Her affidavit filed 10 October 2025;

(c) Her affidavit filed 17 November 2025;

(d) Affidavit of Mr G filed 10 October 2025;

(e) Affidavit of Ms P filed 10 October 2025;

(f) Affidavit of Dr DD filed 10 October 2025;

(g) Affidavit of Mr EE filed 10 October 2025;

(h) Affidavit of Ms FF filed 10 October 2025;

(i) Affidavit of Ms GG filed 27 September 2023;

(j) Notice of Child Abuse Family Violence or Risk filed 10 October 2025;

(k) Financial Statement filed 10 October 2025;

(l) Undertaking as to Disclosure filed 10 October 2025;

(m) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 8 November 2023;

(n) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 25 September 2024; and

(o) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 24 October 2025.

The father relied upon the following documents at the final hearing as set out in his Case Outline:
(a) Further Further Amended Response to Initiating Application filed 13 October 2025;

(b) His affidavit filed 17 October 2025;

(c) Affidavit of Dr HH filed 17 October 2025;

(d) Affidavit of Ms JJ filed 17 October 2025;

(e) Affidavit of dated Ms KK sworn 17 October 2025;

(f) Affidavit of Mr LL filed 17 October 2025;

(g) Affidavit of Ms MM filed 12 October 2025;

(h) Financial Statement filed 17 October 2025;

(i) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 8 November 2023;

(j) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 22 August 2024;

(k) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 25 September 2024; and

(l) Single Expert Report by Dr N dated 24 October 2025.

I have read all the evidence relied upon and tendered in these proceedings, but do not propose to repeat the entirety in these reasons. As the High Court sets out in Whisprun Pty Ltd v Dixon [2003] HCA 48; (2003) 200 ALR 447 at [62]:
... A judge’s reasons are not required to mention every fact or argument relied on by the losing party as relevant to an issue. Judgments of trial judges would soon become longer than they already are if a judge's failure to mention such facts and arguments would be evidence that he or she had not properly considered the losing party’s case.

THE LAW

The competing applications for parenting orders are informed by considering the statutory criteria to determine orders that are in the best interests of X and Y as the paramount consideration pursuant to s 60CA of the Act. The matters to be taken into account by the Court in determining the best interests of the children are identified in s 60CC(2).
Section 60B of the Act outlines the objects and principles underlying Part VII, being to ensure that the best interests of children are met, including by ensuring their safety, and to give effect to the Convention on the Rights of the Child.
The Court must, pursuant to s 60CC(2A), consider any history of family violence, abuse, or neglect involving the child or a person caring for the child, and any family violence order that applies or has applied to the child or a member of the child’s family.
The Court must, pursuant to s 60CG consider the risk of family violence and to the extent it is possible to do so consistently with the child’s best interests being the paramount consideration, ensure that the order is consistent with any family violence order and does not expose a person to an unacceptable risk of family violence.

WHAT PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY ORDERS ARE IN THE CHILDREN’S BEST INTERESTS

Although both parents sought orders that the children spend significant time with the father, and there was no contest that each had the capacity to provide for the development, psychological, emotional and cultural needs of the children, the mother sought orders for sole decision-making responsibility.
The mother contended that issues of family violence, the type of family violence perpetrated at various points in the relationship, the mother’s response to family violence in the context of her history, the work undertaken by the parties with their individual therapists and their ability to co-parent in the future were relevant to the determination of parental responsibility and to school choice.
The father sought joint long-term decision-making responsibility which he contended was necessary to prevent the marginalisation of his role with the children and to prevent him becoming “sidelined” in his role as their father, which he contended was not in the children’s best interests.
Dr N observed in the 2025 Single Expert Report that the mother’s proposal that she be granted sole parental responsibility “would protect the children from exposure to ongoing parental conflict”. He opined that joint decision-making responsibility would “perpetuate the current issues associated with the lack of mutual respect, trust and goodwill which impedes communication and problem solving.” This weighs in favour of an order for sole decision‑making authority being held by the mother.
In his oral evidence, however, Dr N opined that the mother should not hold sole decision making in respect of the children’s names, religion and where the children live and he supported a restraint on further relocations by the mother.
Dr N also identified that an order for sole decision-making responsibility may result in the exclusion of the father and paternal family from involvement in the children’s lives, as feared by the father.
I have carefully considered the opinion of Dr N as set out in each of the four reports he prepared from 2023 to 2025, and have considered and give weight to the opinions he expressed when he gave his oral evidence. I accept, as identified by Dr N, that the level of distrust and dysfunctional communication between these parents is a strong indicator against an order for joint decision-making responsibility.
However, another significant consideration in determining decision-making responsibility is the extent to which the mother has made unilateral decisions, excluded the father from decisions and failed to inform him of significant issues impacting the children, thus marginalising the capacity of the father to be informed and involved in decisions impacting the children. That exclusion and potential loss of connection between the children and the father and paternal family, particularly given the young ages of the children, is of concern and weighs against an order for sole decision-making authority being held by the mother.
It is balancing these competing considerations that is at the nub of the determination of what orders for decision-making are in the best interests of these children.

Allegations of family violence

The mother alleged that the father perpetrated family violence against her in the form of coercive and controlling behaviour and abusive behaviour. It was contended that these allegations were relevant to the determination of parental responsibility.

Coercive and controlling family violence

In determining whether behaviour constitutes coercive or controlling conduct, McClelland DCJ in the Full Court decision of Pickford & Pickford [2024] FedCFamC1A 249; (2024) FLC 94-230 (“Pickford”) stated at [31] that this required a “deeper evaluation than simply a party’s experience or perception – as relevant as that may be.” His Honour adopted the analysis of Gill J in Olivier & Olivier [2020] FamCA 639 (“Olivier & Olivier”), where His Honour observed:
It should be accepted that the definition of family violence goes well beyond physical assaults to encompass behaviours that, absent context may appear innocuous, but in context may be examples of coercion or control. However, the mere assertion that the conduct has the quality of being coercive or controlling does not make it so. It is necessary that the evidence, particularly where the behaviour is ambiguous and may bear an innocuous explanation, be sufficient to allow a characterisation of coercion or control.
By way of example, a pattern of disagreements and criticism can form controlling or coercive behaviour. Whether they do or not must be derived from consideration of their form, intensity, context and the impact upon a person. The mere fact of disagreement or criticism does not automatically equate to family violence.
(Emphasis added)
In Pickford, Aldridge and Carew JJ articulated the necessary forensic examination, assessment of weight and evaluation required to make findings in respect of such allegations:
The focus of the fact finding process is on the behaviour and the impact of the behaviour. It is the behaviour that coerces or controls. It requires action and reaction. A single act is unlikely to be coercive or controlling but it may be. Behaviour that coerces or controls may be innocuous, subtle, capable of different interpretations, complex, undermining, etc. Such behaviour may create impossible expectations for the other family member. It may be transactional and involve punishments for perceived failures. The impact of the behaviour can be insidious. A confident and happy family member may lose their confidence, their self-esteem, question their sanity, shun their family and friends, become depressed, irritable, inefficient, and unhappy. There may be times when they strike out either verbally or physically.
When determining an allegation that a person has engaged in behaviour that coerces or controls a family member, a trial judge will undertake a forensic examination of all relevant evidence to:
(a) identify the behaviour about which complaint is made;

(b) identify the full context of the behaviour including any explanation that may be given by the alleged perpetrator;

(c) identify the impact of the behaviour on the alleged victim (mere assertion by the alleged victim that they feel coerced or controlled is insufficient);

(d) make all relevant factual findings; and

(e) explain why the behaviour in question is or is not family violence that coerces or controls the family member and if the alleged behaviour does not entail a course or pattern of conduct, explain how the behaviour can nevertheless be characterised as behaviour that coerces or controls, if so found.

Once such behaviour has been identified it is then a question of what weight is to be given to it and any impact on the orders under consideration.
The definition of family violence is necessarily broad and any interpretation that may be perceived to, or actually, create unnecessary hurdles to an alleged victim proving an allegation of family violence should be avoided.
Whilst the key feature of coercion or control is that a person is induced (many other words are also apt here) to do as the other wishes, the statutory focus is simply on behaviour that coerces or controls and not the intention of the perpetrator.
So understood, the finding that there is coercive or controlling behaviour is an evaluative one, having regard to all of the circumstances and all of the evidence before the court. Whilst patterns of behaviour may be particularly illuminative, they are not essential. Importantly, for present purposes, the trial judge does not need to spend time and trouble searching for an inference that there is an intention to coerce or control. It is sufficient simply to apply the words of the statute without embellishment and assess whether there is behaviour that coerces or controls.
It must be recognised that, particularly in parenting matters, parents will often disagree. Matters may be seen as proper or as coercive or controlling depending on the circumstances. For example, a proposal that a child be seen by a particular doctor, that changeovers take place in a particular manner or that a certain person not be alone with the children are all capable of being seen as both reasonable and proper parenting proposals or may also be examples of coercive or controlling behaviour.

Allegation that the father perpetrated coercive and controlling family violence

The mother bears the onus of establishing the case she advances on the balance of probabilities (s 140 of the Evidence Act 1995 (Cth)). The mother gave evidence of the incidents she says were of emotional abuse and conduct that was coercive and controlling family violence that she said was perpetrated upon her by the father.

Communication, demeaning texts and the April 2023 Hens party

The mother made allegations the father was coercive and controlling during the relationship, was emotionally abusive, stalked and psychologically threatened her and she reported that he had restricted contact with her friends and family. She said that he was still a stalking risk to her. The mother reported to her treating psychologist, Ms P (who she commenced seeing in March 2024), “an extended period of domestic abuse and coercive control which escalated following their separation.”
The mother deposed that during the relationship the father frequently called her “dumb”, “stupid”, “a bogan” and a “stupid fucking bitch”, including when the children were present. The father agreed he said “slit your wrists you psycho” on 20 October 2022 and that he verbally denigrated the mother by reference to her intelligence. He agreed that he had called her “dumb”, “stupid” and “a bogan” and said that some of his comments were said in front of the children.
The mother gave evidence that she was required to have a nanny present to oversee her at all times if she went out, complained of a lack of privacy, and gave an example of the control being illustrated by questions as to why she was longer than 15 minutes in the shower. The mother deposed that the derogatory taunts and abuse and oversight was ongoing throughout the marriage.
The mother gave evidence of the father’s behaviour after she attended a “Hens party” of her friend in April 2023, where there was a dispute about the time she was to return home. The text messages sent by the father in April 2023 were arrogant, belittling, demeaning and offensive. He directed that the mother was to transfer to him $360 to cover the nanny’s costs and referred to her as “an extremely stupid woman”. The text exchanges included the father asking the mother to take three months away from work and accusing the mother of putting her job ahead of their marriage. The messages do not reflect well on the father.
The mother gave evidence of further conflict between the parties following the wedding of the same friend they attended later that month.
The mother’s reports to Dr N of isolation from family as a form of coercion and control is at odds with her evidence that she had a complex history with her family, particularly her mother, including a period of estrangement from her mother of a decade and a complex childhood impacted by her mother’s psychological health.
The mother reported to Dr N ongoing communication and support from friends such that her reports of isolation from friends because of the father is inconsistent with these reports. The mother reported to Dr N that she kept in touch with her friends and had kept a diary of the father’s behaviours at the suggestion of one of her friends. No witness was called by the mother, and the “DV diary”, although requested in a Notice to Produce, was never produced and was not part of her evidence. If the mother had contemporaneous notes corroborating her evidence it is unexplained why they were not produced.
The mother gave evidence that she had been away for work for several days in March 2023 and that she had not responded to a message sent by the father about Y’s sleeping. She complained that the father had ignored her text messages and calls the following day. She gave evidence of him minimising her work successes, requiring her to leave a work awards event when Y could not be settled and criticising her work choices.
The mother complained the father took pictures of her. She also deposed that after she had taken a photograph of the father at changeover on 11 January 2024, he sent her an abusive message the following day, saying:
Clearly something creepy and surreptitious (look it up) behind your actions on Thursday. I am not comfortable with you taking photos of me. Do not do so again. Do not engage or talk with me at drop off. I have no wish to speak to you. You always escalate to conflict in front of the children and I prefer to avoid that.
The mother complained that the father would not communicate at handover and of his abusive behaviour. The mother deposed that she attended handover with Mr G and his children on 25 January 2024. Her evidence was that “[Mr G] and his children were also in the car, where they remained with the windows wound up.” She said that the father then went over to the car and took photos of Mr G yelling abuse, including “[d]on’t ever come to the property again! You’re a scumbag mate!”.
The father then sent the picture he had taken of Mr G to the mother’s uncle. The event reflects poorly on both parents. On the mother, firstly by taking Mr G to the property when there was tension and mistrust between the parties, and secondly by her sworn evidence that Mr G remained in the car “with the windows wound up” when the photograph depicts Mr G with the window down, his elbow out of the window, smiling toward the camera. On the father, firstly by yelling and being abusive to Mr G, and secondly, by being unable to restrain himself from such conduct in the presence of not only his own children but also Mr G’s children.
The father agreed that on 13 September 2023 he said to Ms Q he “might just obliterate” the mother and it was “time for her to feel the boot psychologically and financially.” The language he used is aggressive, threatening and concerning. It is the context of the language that is important in considering the mother’s case that the father was coercive and controlling and thus a perpetrator of family violence.
In explaining his words to Ms Q, the father said that at the time he made the comment, he had just received a text from the mother that she had taken the children. The mother sent a text to the father at 2.25 pm advising she had taken the children. It was suggested that he did not receive or see the message until after the appointment because Ms Q had not recorded any detail of him having received a text message in her notes. I accept the father’s evidence as to the timing of the counselling appointment and the receipt of the message because he had an appointment scheduled that afternoon with Ms Q, and his explanation as to his high emotion and inappropriate comments made at the time he was advised that the mother had left with the children is inherently likely.
The mother’s application for parenting orders and affidavit in support was served on the father’s lawyers on 13 September 2023. This day was one of high emotion for the parties and was the day of final separation. I accept that the father’s comments on this occasion were as he explained, highly charged and emotive in the context of the parties’ separation and having been told the mother had taken the children, rather than a course of conduct as contended.
The mother contended that the father’s hostility and attempts to control her have continued since separation. She gave evidence that after she left the home, the father set up additional cameras in the home, and on an occasion, recorded her on his mobile phone. The father agreed that on 20 October 2023 he had advised the mother he had additional cameras at the house and on an occasion when the mother attended the home and the parties had a dispute over a music box, the father had recorded the mother. Despite requests to produce the recordings, the father did not do so. If the father had a recording of the interaction between the parties that corroborated his version it is unexplained why he did not produce it.
There was also mutual poor communication between the parties that occurred during the period around separation and after separation. In many instances, such as the refusal to reply to each other when the mother attended an event in March 2023 and the taking of pictures of each other at handover, the conduct has a flavour of tit-for-tat.
On 20 October 2023, shortly after separation, the mother attended the family home to collect belongings that were agreed to by the father. In addition to the items that were agreed, the mother deposed that she “picked up the children’s music box which they liked to help them sleep”. She said that the father then snatched the music box from her hands and knocked her and Y over in the process, and then called for his friend present in the house to call the police, claiming that the mother had assaulted him. The father agreed there was an incident but said the mother pushed him backwards, causing him to accidentally trip Y over. The mother said she was fearful and left immediately with Y, making a police report herself about the incident. She contended that this was an example of the father’s lack of insight and the impact of the father’s conduct on the mother.
The mother sought to take an item not agreed. The father could simply have agreed to the mother taking the music box. Equally, the mother could simply have collected the agreed items and not sought to remove an additional item. The behaviour of both parties at this time was poor and highlights the extent of the conflict and high emotion in the time around separation.
After separation, there was conflict in respect of some parenting issues such as a complaint the father made of the children living in an “insect infected abode” on 26 December 2023. The language used was critical of the mother’s care of the children. More recently, there was conflictual communication between the parents over a dispute as to the appropriate treatment for a suspected tick.
After careful consideration of the evidence and the context in which it occurred, I find that the father was emotionally abusive and denigrated the mother’s intelligence both during the relationship and shortly after separation. The father’s conduct prior to and at the time of separation included using language that was demeaning and denigrating. It was inappropriate and would have been upsetting for the mother, particularly given the mother’s developmental vulnerabilities and her experience of having been exposed to coercion and control in her childhood by her parents, as identified by Ms P.
I am not satisfied on the balance of probabilities that the mother was subject to the claimed control and isolation by the father that she contended. Additionally, her claim of oversight, control and lack of privacy was inconsistent with her engagement in a clandestine relationship with Mr G over many months, undetected.
The father gave evidence that he completed a 12-week in-person Men’s Behavioural Change Program in June 2024. He also completed two parenting courses which he said have helped him learn about working cooperatively with the other parent, managing conflict and endeavouring to focus on the interests of the children by minimising the conflict between the parties. He said one of the techniques he learned was to “not allow a cycle of spiralling” and to let the conversation end, rather than make tit-for-tat accusations. I accept the father’s evidence that he has made efforts to work on improving his previous poor behaviours and inappropriate communication style and now has a greater appreciation of the impact of his behaviour on the mother. I also accept that the father has at times failed to employ the techniques he claimed to have learned in some ongoing inappropriate communication with the mother.

Stalking allegations – ongoing risk claim

The father hired a private investigator and checked the odometer of the mother’s car.
As set out in the Australasian Institute of Judicial Administration, National Domestic Violence Bench Book (last updated in August 2025) at chapter 3.1.6, “harassing or monitoring may be one aspect of a complex pattern of behaviours engaged in by perpetrators in order to control another person” which is a form of family violence by coercive control. The mother said the father’s conduct in hiring a private investigator and checking her odometer was part of the pattern of coercive and controlling behaviour.
The father’s conduct in checking the odometer on an occasion where he suspected the mother was being untruthful to him and Ms Q, and engaging a private investigator to determine whether the wife had gone away for work when he believed she was having a relationship, does not reflect well on him. The father acknowledged his poor conduct. His behaviour was poor and intrusive on the occasions it occurred, however, considering the context, timing, and the extent of the behaviour (being limited to the identified occasions), it is not behaviour that in my view establishes a pattern of behaviour or meets the definition of coercive and controlling family violence as contended.
Accordingly, I do not accept, as claimed by the mother, that the father continues to pose a risk of such behaviour.

Family violence perpetrated by the mother

The mother accepted that she slapped the father in late 2023 following the father referring to the maternal grandmother as a ‘child abuser’ while the mother had the maternal grandmother on loudspeaker on a call. The mother consented to an ADVO being issued against her the following day, and she was charged with the assault which she plead guilty to. No conviction was recorded, and the offence was dealt with by way of a Conditional Release Order for a period of 12 months commencing from mid- 2024.
The father accepted that he called the maternal grandmother a child abuser, after the maternal grandmother had earlier prevented X from using the toilet inside the house. The father knew of the maternal grandmother’s Obsessive Compulsive Disorder (OCD). He knew of the difficulties in the relationship between the mother and the maternal grandmother and accepted that in this situation he could have shown empathy towards the mother for the situation she was in.
The incident, only days prior to the parties’ final separation, highlights that around this time the parties were in high conflict. Both parties behaved poorly.

The mother’s conduct excluding the father from information and decision-making

The mother’s conduct in unilaterally moving the children away from Suburb B and moving further away on two more occasions without notice; enrolling the children in F School without the father’s consent and without notice in February 2024; her failure to inform the father (or the Court) about X having regular “blackouts” where she was unable to regulate her behaviour and emotions sometimes lasting up to 10 minutes; her dishonesty with the father about Mr G’s role in disciplining X; and the conflicting evidence between the mother and Mr G about the name change discussion with X, all leave little optimism that the mother would exercise sole decision-making responsibility in a manner that would keep the father informed and involved. This past conduct informs the likely future conduct of the mother and does not support the sole decision-making order she seeks.

The mother’s enrolment of children at F School and refusal to complete forms to hold a place in U School

The mother agreed she had completed the enrolment for the girls to attend F School in March or April 2024 and had taken the girls on two tours of F School between May and August 2024. She did not inform the father of the enrolment or the tours, nor invite him to participate. The mother said she was confident X would not be impacted by this as she understood she “might” as opposed to “would” be attending the school.
When the father sought to enrol the children at U School, the mother objected to the children being interviewed because she said it would be confusing for the children as they were already aware of three school options. Her approach was internally inconsistent.

The father’s insight

Dr N observed that around the time of separation the father had become depressed, acted in an angry and threatening manner, and was suspicious. His conduct referred to above is consistent with that observation.
The father relied on evidence from his treating psychologist, Ms MM. Ms MM gave detailed evidence of the treatment she has provided since April 2024 and of the father’s progress in respect of his parenting. She opined that the father continues to present with relationship distress and adjustment stressors, but that their sessions have been beneficial to him in coping with his grief symptoms while “fostering emerging awareness of the relational factors influencing the co-parenting dynamic” and working on emotional regulation and reflective functioning. She said that he has shown active engagement and commitment in their treatment sessions. The treatment in these sessions includes personal-centred therapy, trauma-informed Cognitive Behaviour Therapy, mindfulness-based Cognitive Therapy and psychoeducation. She opined that the father is “very motivated to engage in further restorative conciliation.”
Ms MM was not required for cross-examination. I accept her uncontested evidence.
The mother contended that the father’s inflexibility in changing arrangements, which were reasonably requested, supported the making of an order for sole decision making in respect of parental responsibility. She gave various examples including the camping trip of January 2024 and the Mother’s Day 2025 request in support of the contention that the father lacked insight.
In respect of the Mother’s Day request, it was accepted it was received only days prior to the event and the response was that arrangements had already been made for that weekend. It was not unreasonable that the father refused a late request when plans for his otherwise quite limited time had already been made.
The father refused the mother’s proposal during January 2024 for the children to attend a camping trip from 15 to 21 January 2024 in circumstances where he knew he would be away on a trip in Country NN. His refusal in this instance lacked insight and child focus. The father’s oral evidence was that the trip was a family trip agreed to in May or June 2023. The itinerary produced evidenced only a single adult airfare to travel to Country NN from mid-January until late January 2024, and not for a family trip. This lack of transparency with the Court and his explanation it was a family trip is not supported on the independent evidence.
In this instance the father was aware of his travel plans and his refusal to vary the time which would have enabled the children to engage in a camping experience shows a lack of flexibility and insight at this time and reflects poorly on him. Equally, the father’s rigidity in refusing to alter the weekend arrangements to coincide with Mr G’s children’s time appears to have been a petty and inflexible approach by the father, particularly because if he had altered the arrangement, it could have been an indicator of a positive and cooperative co-parenting relationship.
The mother, through her lawyers, asked the father if they could push back the changeover time to 9.30 am on Saturday to allow her the option of travelling with the children by train. His lawyers responded with questions about the details of the travel and arrangement. The father’s evidence was that he needed clarity on the travel arrangements to understand whether the children would be exhausted from an arduous travel journey. He accepted it would not have inconvenienced him significantly. However, he said that he sees his elderly father on Saturdays and that might have been a factor he had to consider, but that he could not recall exactly why he did not accept that change in travel that day. The father lacked flexibility and lacked child focus in this refusal. He knew the train travel was from the City H area and would have given the mother respite from the driving commitments, which were significant. This again reflects poorly on him.
The father accepted that these were not examples of him implementing what he had learned from the courses he participated in and from his work with the Men’s Behaviour Change Program with Mr OO. In his oral evidence he acknowledged his shortcomings, and I accept his evidence that he is always learning new ways to improve the co-parenting relationship, that the course has not completed him as a good co-parent but that he is constantly working on that. It does not detract from his past inflexible and at times petty responses to co-parenting, but gives some optimism for improvement.

The poor view of the father held by the mother and Mr G

The mother and Mr G have historically had, and continue to hold, a poor view of the father. Dr N said in oral evidence there was no doubt that the mother and Mr G continued to view the father as a threat to the integrity of their evolving family unit. He observed in his report that “[i]t was unfortunate that, despite the evidence that the father did not pose a risk to the mother, her partner or the children, the mother and her partner maintained the position that he did and that it would be unsafe to disclose the location of their residence.”
Dr N observed at paragraph 200 of his 2025 Single Expert Report that:
... [the mother] asserted that the father’s intransigence had resulted in the current stressful travel requirements for her and the children despite it being evident that her actions had resulted in an expansion of the travel requirements. Somewhat surprisingly, she had difficulty in acknowledging that this was the case.
There were many examples of the poor view the mother and Mr G held about the father. The following examples illustrate the extent and nature of this view.

The disclosure by Y about being touched in the red zone

In March 2024, Y told her father that Mr G had touched her in her red zone. The following day, after the father had taken her to a GP, the father made a formal allegation to the police regarding Y’s disclosure to him that Mr G touched her in her “red zone”. His lawyers informed the mother that an allegation had been made.
The mother informed Department of Communities and Justice (DCJ) in March 2024 that Mr G had once assisted Y with toileting. The mother subsequently swore an affidavit in May 2024 deposing that Mr G had not previously assisted the children with toileting. Mr G deposed in October 2024 that he once helped Y wipe her bottom after she had “done a poo” while the mother was present.
The mother maintained her narrative that the father fabricated a report that Y said Mr G touched her in her “red zone.” In her sworn evidence, the mother deposed that she did not believe that Y made the allegation the father claimed she did. The mother largely maintained this position in her oral evidence. She answered in cross-examination that Y’s comment to her father that she had a sore “bum-bum” was taken out of context and was then used by the father to lie and manufacture a malicious allegation.
The mother started seeing her clinical psychologist, Ms P, on 26 March 2024 and in a report dated 17 April 2024, Ms P recorded that the mother had told her that DCJ had determined the father’s claim to have been vexatious.
Because of the claimed false or vexatious report, the mother sought supervised time between the father and the children. The father then had limited supervised time with the children for a period of time.
Dr N accepted the proposition that the depth of antipathy held by the mother to the father was illustrated by the mother’s maintaining her steadfast belief that the father had made up allegations in circumstances where Mr G had assisted with toileting at the time the concern was legitimately raised and the disclosure was made in language that Y uses. In cross-examination, the mother simultaneously accepted that Mr G had touched X in her “red zone”, but maintained that the father had made up the allegation. The mother did not seem to appreciate that such a position was illogical and illustrates the depth of the animus she holds.

Mr G’s discipline of X

Another illustration of the poor view the mother and Mr G have of the father is the narrative they maintained, including in their oral evidence, that the father had falsely accused Mr G of disciplining X.
A report was made by X to the father in the presence of a supervisor who recorded in the supervision notes on 5 July 2024:
[X] told [the father], she doesn’t like going to [Mr G’s] house because he isn’t nice and a bad person. [The father] told her he was a nice person and [X] said he isn’t because he put her outside. [The father] asked why and [Y] said [Mr G] put her outside because [X] was screaming. [X] asked [the father] not to tell her mother and she began to cry. [The father] picked [X] up and they cuddled as she cried, [the father] warmly reassured and comforted her, and he told [X] she was a good girl ...
The father then through his lawyers on 8 July 2024 sought an explanation about X’s complaint of Mr G disciplining X by locking her outside. The mother replied through her lawyers in a letter dated 12 July 2024, which said:
... The words your client attributes to [X] more properly reflect your client’s views about [Mr G]. That said, my client denies that [Mr G] has ever locked [X] outside. The disciplinary measure taken by my client when [X] is acting out is a short “time-out” in the lounge room.
In oral evidence, it was revealed by Mr G that he had been involved in the children’s discipline at this time. Mr G gave oral evidence about X having “blackouts” in 2024 lasting up to 10 minutes, due to a loss of control of her emotional regulation. He said this would occur once or twice a week but is now happening approximately once a month. He said he was involved in her discipline which included placing her outside during such periods.
In response to the father’s reasonable request for information about the discipline of the children the mother was misleading about the discipline of X undertaken by Mr G.
Neither the mother nor Mr G deposed in their sworn evidence about the blackouts and the emotional dysregulation of X or the discipline of X by Mr G, including him putting her outside during periods of dysregulation. I find that they were both less than frank by this omission.
Dr N confirmed that he was aware of the use of “Time-Out strategies” for managing X’s meltdowns but gave oral evidence that he had not been provided with the details that X had exhibited behaviours that led to her blacking out for up to 10 minutes at a time because she was unable to regulate herself. This was important information to withhold.
The mother reported to Dr N that her experience was that the father continued to pursue her partner, Mr G, despite there being “a lack of evidence to support the father’s concerns that the children were at risk of child sexual abuse or inappropriate discipline in the care of the mother and her partner, [Mr G].”
The mother was not a frank witness about the issues of X’s blackouts, the extent of her dysregulation or of the discipline of X by Mr G. She did not include any detail of X’s dysregulated behaviour in her sworn evidence, and the father was positively told by her lawyers that Mr G was not involved in the disciplining of the children when this was untrue. The mother maintained her narrative that she did not accept X held the view that Mr G had been “mean” to her, when she well knew that he had been involved in the discipline of X, when it was recorded in the L Contact Service notes and when the father had raised concerns about it.
The mother claimed the children would never see her poor view of him. It was contended that there is no evidence that X and Y are currently aware of the poor view held by the mother and Mr G of the father, such that there is no risk to the relationship because the children have been shielded from the animus. I do not accept that contention in circumstances where Y was recorded in the L Contact Service notes from 14 June 2024 saying to her father “Mummy doesn’t like you”, and when Dr N asked X what Mr G and her father thought about each other, she stated to him that they had bad thoughts about each other. Additionally, their older stepsisters were present on the occasions that Mr G attended the home for changeover when the father was angered by his presence and made abusive comments toward Mr G when he was in the car. The mother accepted that Mr G’s children feared the father and said something like “he looks like he’s mad” about the father.
The children have been exposed to the poor view held by the mother’s household of the father and it is reasonable to infer they will continue to be. There is an awareness of the mother’s and Mr G’s feelings towards the father, and of the tensions between the father and Mr G. In my view, given the history, it is more likely than not that the children will become more aware of the poor view of their father in the mother’s household, particularly as they grow older.
Dr N observed at paragraph 208 of his August 2024 Single Expert Report that:
The mother was observed to have overtly influenced the children in their views regarding their family. Thus, they were encouraged to refer to [Mr G’s] daughters as sisters and [Y] started referring to him as “Daddy”. There was no indication that she had acted to support the children’s relationship with their father.
Dr N opined that the impact on the children of the mother encouraging the children to refer to Mr G as “Daddy” and his daughters as “sisters” will necessarily undermine the children’s perception of the importance of the father’s role in their lives which will encourage the children, “at their tender age”, to perceive that their mother is supported by Mr G as their primary carers.
Dr N opined that the mother will continue to overly influence the children’s views regarding their family as she is the primary influence on the children’s views and there is no indication that this would be likely to change. He considered that this would be further influenced by the loss of regular contact with their father.
Dr N expressed the opinion that the mother will not support the children’s relationship with their father and observed that she has not been doing so since at least February 2024. His view was “reinforced” when the mother enrolled the children at F School without informing the father.
Dr N’s opinion was not meaningfully challenged and I accept it.
I find the mother and Mr G have entrenched views about the father which are poor and there is a risk that he will be marginalised in the children’s lives. The mother and Mr G lacked frankness with the Court about these matters which causes me to have reservation in accepting the mother has given a complete account of matters when she perceived they may not have assisted her case.
The past conduct referred to above and the poor view the mother has of the father supports that an order for joint decision-making rather than sole decision-making is in the best interests of the children, as such an order is protective of the relationship between the children and the father.

The level of distrust and poor communication

There was no dispute, as observed by Dr N, that the parties have high levels of distrust and very poor communication. Dr N characterised the co-parenting relationship as high conflict.
Dr N gave evidence of a pattern of ongoing and enduring lack of respect, trust and goodwill between the parties which caused them to regard each other’s behaviours as provocative stating:
The first point that I would make is that there has been an ongoing and enduring lack of respect and trust and goodwill between the parties. Therefore, when there has been concerns held by one or other of the parties, they approach the other party with suspicion and, certainly, each have regarded the other’s behaviour as provocative. There has been, on occasion, particularly in the past, raised voices, allegations, the children being exposed to the parents’ hostility towards each other. Although that has improved, that has now been extended to the interactions between the father and the mother’s new partner, [Mr G], and that has been an ongoing cause for concern and, at the end of the day, the parties have been unable to approach each other with respectful communication, whereby the mother could feel comfortable to disclose her location of residence. The father has continued to be frustrated by the mother’s – his experience of the mother’s obstruction to him having ongoing – an ongoing significant and substantive relationship with his children and the mother has experienced the father’s attempts to not engage in dialogue which the father has felt to be provocative as further evidence of his coercive and controlling behaviour where he won’t respond to her communication. And so that has been an ongoing pattern.

(Transcript 24 November 2025, p.516 lines 3–19)
Poor communication risks exposing the children to conflict if the parties are required to make joint decisions.
Fortunately, many of the long-term issues that had been in dispute have been resolved by consent, including a restraint on the mother relocating further away, a restraint on changing the names of the children, a restraint on changing the schools and the maintenance of the Sydney school enrolment.
The dispute as to the school the children shall attend has been resolved by these orders.
Ms P prepared three reports which were received into evidence. She reported in August 2025 that (at p.28):
Her anxiety regarding her ex-partner’s behaviour has somewhat reduced, and she demonstrates increased capacity to manage associated stressors in a more positive way. Notably, her concerns are now expressed more thoughtfully and with less panic. She actively employs cognitive and polyvagal regulation strategies introduced during therapy.
It is agreed that communication has been undertaken successfully using the OurFamilyWizard application and an order for communication in this form has been made by consent. The consequence of this order is that if there is a need to communicate about long-term decisions, there is an agreed forum for this to occur.
Finally, both parties gave evidence of the significant efforts that they each have made working with respective psychologists to address their identified individual parenting and communication challenges and shortcomings. If there is difficulty in communication in the future, the parents are each supported by a positive therapeutic relationship.
Each of these factors indicate that although there have been difficulties in the past and a lack of effective communication, the parties have taken steps to improve that dynamic, they have therapeutic supports to assist if necessary and the long-term issues that can be anticipated are significantly reduced by reason of the orders made, thus limiting the need for communication.

Counselling for the children

The only major long-term issue apparent at the present time is whether and which treating therapist X should attend upon for counselling. An order directing the means by which the parties will facilitate the children’s attendance on a counsellor will overcome any issue of poor communication having a deleterious impact on the children by exposure to conflict or by delay in a decision being reached, in respect of this defined issue.
Dr N identified that X has been a “people pleaser”. During the evidence, it became apparent that X has had significant “meltdowns” or “blackouts” and suffered emotional dysregulation when in the care of the mother. No information about this concerning behaviour had been shared with the father.
The mother initially did not acknowledge that the move from Sydney to the City H area and into a new home with new siblings, a new parental figure, and away from the father and paternal family, may have negatively impacted the children. In cross-examination, the mother conceded that the children were impacted by the swiftness of these changes.
Dr N agreed with the proposition that both parents should be involved to the maximum extent possible in any therapy for X. Given the evidence of X’s emotional dysregulation, I am satisfied that such an order is in her best interests. It is accordingly appropriate that an order be made for a mechanism for the children to attend upon a therapist, should either parent seek such to occur, and prescriptive for the process of selection of a therapist if the children or either of them attends counselling, such that both parents can be involved to the maximum extent possible.
If either parent wishes for either child to attend a therapist or psychologist and the parties cannot come to an agreement as to a counsellor or psychologist, the mother shall nominate three practitioners, and the father shall select the practitioner to be seen. This is to avoid the parties being in conflict about the selection of a practitioner and to avoid any delay in the process of selection of a practitioner. It also creates a framework to minimise dispute and create certainty of timeframe and the practitioner.

Conclusion

Although it is very finely balanced in this case, the risk of the father being excluded from decision-making and having information withheld by the mother, outweighs the risks that arise from future poor co-parenting and communication. Such an order is protective in nature as it prevents animus that has existed from motivating withholding of information or provision of inaccurate information as to major long-term issues. As above, it is significant that several long-term issues have been resolved by orders made by consent, and by these orders, the dispute as to which school the children will attend has also been determined. The parents will hold joint decision-making responsibility because the risk of the father being marginalised from the children’s lives absent such an order is more significant a risk than exposure to poor co‑parenting and communication on long term issues.

WHAT ORDERS FOR TIME WITH THE FATHER ARE IN THE CHILDREN’S BEST INTERESTS

The dispute as to time was what transition of time with the father that can be practically implemented is in the best interests of the children.
The mother sought an increase to four nights in 2026, then five nights in 2027.
The father sought an increase to five nights in 2026, then six nights in 2027 if the children attended U School. The father gave evidence that if the children attended F School, he felt the commute between F School and Suburb B for five or six nights would be too onerous, and in that instance, it would be in the best interests of the children to spend alternate weekends in his care, although this was not his preference.
For the reasons that follow, it is in the best interests of the children to spend time with the father for five nights each fortnight during the school term and for this arrangement to continue.

Lack of basic co-operation in an almost shared arrangement

Firstly, Dr N opined that the parents do not have a co-parenting relationship that supports a significant shared care arrangement because of the lack of commonality in the home environments, lack of respect, communication and trust. I accept that a level of basic co‑operation, communication and commonality in household is necessary to make day-to-day arrangements functional in a significant shared care arrangement and these circumstances do not exist.
The absence of capacity to easily engage in regular communication that would be necessary for a successful almost shared arrangement indicates against such orders are in the best interests of the children. Practically, this lack of capacity to engage about day-to-day matters runs the risk of the children being exposed to conflict and may increase the necessity for communication between the parents. Dr N was of the view that the time orders had to be arranged on a practical basis. He further opined that there is a barrier to a significant shared care arrangement. In cross-examination, he gave the following evidence:
Then so – and so if we’re talking about [U School] option, then – and we’re talking about the equally distant arrangement, then I don’t have any comment on the ..... well, I think it would be preferable in that arrangement for the children, at their age now, to spend – to have a primary resident, a primary place of residence, which would be most nights during the week. And so, in those circumstances, I do think that five nights would be preferable to six.

...

The barrier to a significant shared care arrangement in this family has already been identified. The lack of commonality in the home environments being provided by the two households is problematic. The lack of respect, lack of goodwill, lack of communication, lack of trust, all of which make it difficult. And so, you know, is this an arrangement where I could see a successful progression to six nights or a week about shared care? I don’t identify those circumstances.

(Transcript 24 November 2025, p.567 lines 19–25 and lines 30–36)
Dr N was not meaningfully challenged on this evidence. I accept his opinion.

Both parents sought significant time orders

Secondly, both parents sought orders for significant time as being in the best interests of the children, and both sought an increase from the current three nights per fortnight, although at a different rate and increasing to five nights (the mother) and six nights (the father). Orders being made for as much time with the father as can practically work were supported by Dr N and I accept Dr N’s opinion that in the context of a practical arrangement, an order for substantial and significant time with the father is in the children’s best interests. Dr N accepted the proposition that consistency of one particular day in each week with the father was of benefit to the children, in this case the Thursday being “Dad day” which will facilitate extracurricular activities being able to be arranged by the parents each on a consistent day each week.

The benefit of maintaining relationships with both parents

Thirdly, the children are both very young and have had a fractured spend-time arrangement with their father since the parties separated. Despite this, as observed by Dr N, they currently each have a secure and significant attachment relationship with their father. Dr N opined that “[t]he children will benefit from maintaining significant and substantive contact with both parents and the paternal extended family”.
The risk of the children being exposed to the poor view held by the mother and her household about the father, identified earlier in these reasons, can be diluted by the children having their own experience of the father’s household by maximising orders for time that are in their best interests.
Dr N opined, and I accept, that the children will benefit from maintaining significant and substantive contact with both parents and the paternal extended family. He observed, correctly, that the mother’s proposal failed to support the children’s capacity to enjoy significant and substantive contact with the father and paternal extended family.
The five-night regime affords that regular and significant time these young children will require with their father, to ensure a close and positive relationship with each parent, is maintained. It also sets about a set routine from the commencement of school in 2026 that will remain the routine and pattern for the children. Given the significant changes the children have experienced since separation, I am of the view that a certain and regular pattern of time from this point is in the best interests of the children because they will have set days in each household and can attend particular extracurricular activities with their father each Thursday during the school term when they will always be in his care.

The mother’s underlying vulnerabilities

Fourthly, Dr N and Ms P identified that the mother had underlying vulnerabilities arising from her own developmental experience in her family of origin. Dr N opined that her underlying vulnerabilities had not been effectively addressed, despite these being identified both by him and by her treating therapist, Ms P.
The father’s conduct in having sent a message to the mother of one of Mr G’s daughters and to Mr G’s father was perceived by the mother as threatening and scared her. Dr N opined that these behaviours of the father which were both provocative and inappropriate, have been a cause of stress for the mother and have had a serious impact on her. Dr N considered that her earlier developmental experiences with her family of origin and her experiences in the latter stages of her marriage, including the father’s comments on Father’s Day 2023, have made her particularly vulnerable.
Dr N reported that the mother’s therapist, Ms P, has formed a positive and enduring therapeutic alliance with her client, such that the mother has felt respected, supported, and has developed coping strategies in the context of this therapeutic intervention. He said that there was a need for more intensive intervention with Ms P, and reported that Ms P was of the same view and could provide the more intensive intervention. The mother’s evidence was that the lack of time and travel burden to Sydney for school from the City H area has impeded her capacity to engage more regularly. I accept this is the case.
Post-separation, the mother continued to consider the father to be a threat. The mother has not engaged in the supports she needs to address her long-standing vulnerabilities which may impede her capacity to support the relationship between the children and the father. By these orders, the mother will have set times when the children are in the father’s care five nights per fortnight and will not have the significant travel burden between the City H area and Suburb B anymore, which will open more opportunity for her to attend to her therapy needs.
The mother will remain the primary carer for the children, as she has been since at least separation. By these orders, she will be able to engage in her necessary therapy more readily. For her to be psychologically supported and be able to address her long-standing vulnerabilities is in the children’s best interests.

The mother and father’s physical health

The mother has been diagnosed with [redacted] and gave evidence of her concern of the impact of this diagnosis on the parenting orders to be made.
She deposed that her [redacted] has not progressed since January 2022, which was her last episode and course of treatment, and it is mostly well managed through medication with the occasional relapse.
Her evidence was that she requires monthly blood tests reviewed by her GP and biannual health checks by Dr DD, and MRI’s. She deposed that because of the time she spends travelling, “[t]here are not enough hours in the day for me to prioritise these health checks and I have been inconsistent with my monthly blood tests.” She also deposed about her concerns that her inability to undertake activities to maintain her physical health, such as attending the gym, and continuing to sleep for about four hours each night, will negatively impact her [redacted]. The mother was required to undertake six hours of daily travel, 11 days per fortnight in order to comply with the orders. She was awake from 4.00 am and completed her work and domestic tasks, usually at midnight, in order to leave home by 5.30 am for the commute to Sydney. Upon return home after the children were asleep, the mother would have some hours of work and domestic tasks to attend to. There is no doubt the arrangements were arduous.
The mother relied on evidence from her treating clinician. Dr DD said that the mother has done well with treatments and there has been no decline in her capacity and no progression of the disease since her first consultation in 2014. He did not consider that her condition impacted her in any lasting or clinical way. His evidence was not challenged and I accept his evidence.
In considering the practicality of the implementation of orders that are in the children’s best interests, I accept that the mother’s capacity to manage her symptoms by ensuring compliance with blood tests and reviews and by looking after her physical health are relevant and I have regard to these matters.
The father gave evidence in respect of a back condition that he said placed some limit on his capacity to drive long distances. The mother contended the father’s claim regarding his back condition and its impact on his capacity to drive was a confection. I reject that contention. The independent evidence is that the father reported to his GP and to Dr PP that he has had issues relating to pain in his back for a number of years.
Having said that, the evidence before the Court does not permit me to make any finding as to any impediment of the father to drive between Suburb B and the City H area. I am not satisfied, on the balance of probabilities, that the father’s health has any impact on the practical implementation of orders for time.

The children’s cultural needs

Fifthly, there is a risk that the children will lose the benefit of regular and ongoing involvement, connection to and understanding of their paternal family and to their Country QQ heritage, of which the children have been exposed to and aware of since birth by the involvement of the paternal family.
The father contended that the proximity to the paternal family in Suburb B facilitates the children’s connection to their paternal family and a connection to their culture.
The father expressed to Dr N his concern that the “children’s cultural engagement with his extended family had been impeded by the mother’s relocation from Sydney”. Dr N observed that “[t]he children’s cultural needs to maintain a relationship with their [Country QQ] roots had been addressed by the father”. Dr N accepted that weekend time and block time with their father would still enable the children to understand and enjoy their Country QQ heritage. I accept that to be so, however, the nature and extent of their cultural engagement would, by necessity, reduce and thus be impeded.
The paternal grandfather provided evidence of his active involvement with and close relationship with the children. His evidence included his regular involvement with the children, attendance at school events, birthday parties, and sporting events. He described a close and involved relationship with the girls from which they derive benefit. He speaks to the girls about their cultural background and family in Country RR. He was not required for cross‑examination. I accept his evidence.
The paternal aunt gave evidence of her close relationship with the children, and of their close relationship with her children, their cousins, aged three and seven. The aunt spends time with the children at least once a month and on special occasions as well as family catch ups. She was not required for cross-examination. I accept her evidence.
The paternal grandmother gave evidence of her close relationship with the children. She spent regular time during the week and weekends with the children prior to separation and was involved in their care. She speaks to the children about their Country QQ culture and heritage and intends to continue to introduce them to their history, family, food and culture. She was not required for cross-examination, and I accept her evidence.
I accept the evidence of the paternal family of the close and loving relationship they have and of the regular and enjoyable times the children spend with their significant extended family members.
The mother agreed that she had a good relationship with the paternal family prior to separation, that the paternal family are a great resource to the children, that the children benefit from having the maximum amount of involvement with their extended paternal family, and that the paternal family were a valuable connection to the children during the relationship and still are. She acknowledged the positive relationship and the time the paternal family enjoys with the children, including holidays at Suburb SS.
Dr N opined that the mother “failed to recognise the benefit to the children of maintaining a connection with their paternal extended family and [Country QQ] community. As she was estranged from her family of origin, she appeared to underestimate the importance of the children’s extended family.”
Dr N opined, and I accept, that the children would be impacted by not spending as much time with the paternal family both because of the supportive extended family and because of the loss of as much exposure to their Country QQ culture. Significantly reducing the time the children spend with the paternal family and isolating the children from those relationships could deprive the children of a supportive relationship with the paternal extended family into the future.
The children by these orders will live primarily with the mother who will be able to expose them to her Country TT culture and heritage during their time with her, should she wish to do so, including by travel to Country TT. Knowledge and understanding of their cultural heritage is important for the children and I give these matters some weight.

Views expressed by the children

X expressed certain views to Dr N. In 2024 he was of the opinion that the children’s views should be given some, but limited weight given their “tender age”. In his 2025 Single Expert Report, he opined that “[s]ignificant weight should be placed on [X’s] desire to have greater contact with her father while maintaining primary residence with her mother.”
Dr N opined at paragraph 187 of his 2025 Single Expert Report:
It was considered likely that [X] had amplified each parent’s expressed concerns by making statements to each of her loved parents which validated their own views. She had become a “people pleaser” in response to her awareness of their conflictual relationship. This reflected her love and engagement with both parents. Unfortunately, this had served to amplify the parental mistrust.
Dr N agreed that X was displaying the impact of torn loyalties. He also agreed that X might be expressing to her parents conflicting views about what she wants, given the conflict between the parties.
Dr N reported that while X expressed the view that she wished to relocate to F School, there was “every indication” that her wish “had been influenced by her mother and stepfather’s narrative.” Notwithstanding this assessment, Dr N also opined that: “[s]ignificant weight should be placed on [X’s] desire to have greater contact with her father while maintaining primary residence with her mother.”
For these reasons, and her young age, I give X’s expressed views some, but limited weight.

The mother’s evidence about her employment and the practicality of orders

The mother was on notice that her employment requirements were relevant to the consideration of the practical implementation of the orders each party sought. Not only had the issue of her employment and the vague details provided were identified by McGuire J, but the Full Court in Bonhomme & Bonhomme [2025] FedCFamC1A 75 observed that:
Further, at [87] and [126], the primary judge was critical of the mother’s failure to disclose the location and terms of her employment, or indeed any changes to her employment from when she lived in Sydney. It is tolerably clear that the failure to disclose this information was relevant to the alleged “logistical difficulties” created by the mother’s relocation to City H when her place of employment had previously been (and may have continued to be) located near Suburb B.
Notwithstanding this notice of the significance of this issue, the mother gave limited evidence about her employment in her primary affidavit. She was permitted to rely on an affidavit filed on 17 November 2025, giving evidence about a new role she had taken up with UU Company, the same employer as Mr G.
The mother gave evidence that on 17 September 2025 she applied for a role and was interviewed on 13 October and 15 October 2025. On 31 October 2025, she was offered employment with UU Company and accepted it. The mother received her written contract on 13 November 2025 and notified the father on 14 November 2025. The mother also relied on an email from her supervisor, Ms VV, which indicated that she could work from home “when that is permissible” and that most employees work from home on Mondays and Fridays. There are offices of UU Company that are located at Suburb WW, and in City S, although it was unclear when the mother would be working in Sydney, City S or working from home.
The difficulty with the late evidence relied on is that it was general and vague. The mother was uniquely placed to bring evidence to the Court setting out when and where she would be required to work. She could have called evidence from Ms VV, the author of the email. She could have set out with particularity what her expected hours and days were and the location.
The mother gave evidence that she said to Ms VV “it is also important for me to be able to work from the [Suburb XX] office”, to which Ms VV replied:
We are WORK 180 endorsed since 2021, 25% of the organisation are women and we are working to make flexible options even more available wherever possible. We can accommodate the work from home arrangements you have requested. You will also be able to work from the [Suburb XX] office as long as it doesn’t interfere with work on other sites. You will need to work there anyway as part of your role.
In submissions, it was contended she may work from home certain days, she may work from a location near City S, and she may work from Suburb WW. The submission made by her counsel was:
... But the situation in terms of where it is that she can work from in the context of her [...] job is that she can work from home when that’s permissible, and certainly the email from [Ms VV] says that most employees at this organisation work from home on Mondays and Fridays. Certainly, from Tuesday to Thursday, the state of the email from [Ms VV] is that there are satellite offices. The mother further deposes that there are offices of [UU Company] that are located at [Suburb WW], and also about 30 minutes [...] from her home in [City S]. So that is a viable option in respect to that.

(Transcript 26 November 2025, p.763 lines 26–33)
The mother and Mr G both gave evidence that they would be required to work in the Sydney office from time to time. The mother deposed to having an agreement with UU Company that she will work from home two to three days per week, that she can primarily base herself in the Suburb XX office whenever possible, and that she can work from home during the school holiday periods. In her previous working role she was able to work from home five days per week, but she deposed that she was unable to do this because of the current school enrolments.
There is no sound basis to make any finding as to where and on what days the mother will work, other than that she is likely to work from home Mondays and Fridays and that it is likely that the mother will have the benefit of some flexible working arrangements. Her failure to present clear evidence in respect of these matters leaves a lacuna. Her late filing of vague evidence, failure to call evidence from a supervisor who could have illuminated the nature of her flexible work arrangements, and late notice of the change left little opportunity for the father to enquire or issue subpoena. The obligation for disclosure on such a key issue relevant to the determination of the practicality of the proposed arrangements rested with her.
Under the father’s proposed orders, the children would be collected from school Thursday afternoon each week such that there will be no Friday morning school drop-off, and only a Friday afternoon and Monday afternoon collection each alternate week. This arrangement would seem to assist the mother’s work from home arrangement each Monday and Friday, with limited pick-up and drop-offs to and from school. She will still have the burden of ensuring the children get to and from school on the balance of the days that they reside with her each fortnight.
The mother gave oral evidence that if the children attended U School, it would reduce her flexibility to work from home, and she would be burdened by travel if she was working from the Suburb XX office. The mother did not give evidence that she was required to work from the Suburb XX office but that she “can” primarily base herself there presumably for the two to three days per week she is not working from home. Equally, she may be able to primarily base herself in the Sydney office for those days. If she is driving to Sydney, U School is en route. If she is working from home for the anticipated days per week and the school bus service was not used, the burden would fall to the mother. If the children attended F School, the Suburb XX office would be more convenient for the mother and reduce her driving time for school drop off and pick up.
It was not in dispute, and was observed by Dr N, that Mr G had a positive relationship with both children when they interacted. Dr N opined that the blended home environment provided by the mother and Mr G had appropriately met the children’s developmental needs. The children enjoyed their relationship with their mother, her partner, and his children.
Mr G said that he was currently working in the Sydney office at least three days per week. Both the mother and Mr G said Mr G would assist the mother to the extent that he could with school drop-off and pick-up. Mr G is in the fortunate position that he has the support of his mother for the care of his own two children when he is unable to take his children to school due to his work commitments. He gave evidence that both of his daughter’s catch a bus to and from school. These are factors which assist me to find that the mother will have support from Mr G in arranging the logistics of the management of school drop-off and pick-up.
I am unable to make a finding other than the most general of findings in respect of the mother’s employment obligations and its impact on the practicality of time orders being able to be implemented because of the state of the evidence. I accept her evidence that her employer has flexible work arrangements as she deposed. I also accept that she may have to work from time to time from the various offices she identified and take this into consideration in respect of the practicality of the arrangements.

WHETHER THE CHILDREN SHOULD ATTEND SCHOOL AT U SCHOOL OR F SCHOOL

Although the background to this matter involved the mother unilaterally moving the residence of the children from the Suburb B area on several occasions, with her current residence in Suburb AA, being a long distance from Suburb B, the parties agreed the children will reside primarily with the mother in the City H area.
A vexed issue to be determined in these proceedings was the choice of school for the children. As above, the mother proposed F School located in Suburb YY NSW, and the father proposed U School located in Town V NSW. There was no dispute that both schools would provide appropriate education opportunities for the children.
At paragraph 145 of his 2025 Single Expert Report, Dr N identified the real issues in the conflict between the orders the parties sought about school as:
The report writer identified the potential for a “lose/lose compromise” given the difficulty in establishing and maintaining friendship networks and extracurricular activities in the girls’ local area. [The father], however, identified the significance of limiting the children’s contact with him and their extended family in Sydney should the relocation to [F School] be enabled by the Court.
Dr N observed that there would be an ongoing logistical burden for children to travel both ways, and commented that introducing a third location, being U School, would potentially be destabilising.
Dr N identified in his 2025 Single Expert Report that the U School arrangement “would result in the children failing to have a local friendship group from their school and would interfere with their engagement in extracurricular activities.”
Additionally, the children would continue to need to travel approximately 45 minutes by car to U School rather than the less than 10 minutes by car to F School daily on the days they are with their mother. There was evidence of a school bus route from the Town ZZ area to U School departing Town ZZ at 7.05 am, but this would still require travel to deliver the children to the Town ZZ bus stop.
Dr N identified that the father could stay in the Suburb YY area during his off week to spend an afternoon with the children to address the impact of his reduction in the time with the children. The father is not in paid employment and doubtless has the financial capacity and time available to do so, however, as identified by senior counsel, this option raised a “third location” being the obstacle sought to be cured. The time in Suburb YY solution also fails to address the loss of regular connection with the paternal family and culture.
Ms P, in her comprehensive report of 6 October 2025, observed that the lengthy school commute (from the City H area to Suburb B) was a significant source of exhaustion for the mother. She opined that (at p.29):
Clarification of parenting orders that minimise unnecessary contact with her ex-partner would likely support further improvements in her mental health. Relocating the children’s school closer to their primary residence would reduce fatigue and the resulting impact on [the mother] and her children. Such adjustments would also decrease the risk of fatigue-related incidents and bolster overall wellbeing.
The positives of F School included its proximity to the mother’s home and the school community the children would experience, the significantly reduced driving time to and from school during the additional time with their mother, more capacity to attend extracurricular activities in the local areas, the benefit of attending a school with their stepsiblings and the benefit to the mother’s family unit of less logistical issues to manage.
The negatives of F School include practically the limited opportunity for the father to be involved in the day-to-day schooling of the children, with classmates and families of the children, with teachers, and the additional lengthy driving time to spend time with their father five nights per fortnight. If the children attended F School, the meaningful time the father would spend with the children would be reduced and the time the children could spend with the paternal family would also reduce. The suggestion of the father spending time with them in the Suburb YY area has some positives, including the maintenance of the regular time, however, the regular connection with the paternal family would still be diminished. The mother proposed to deliver the children to the AB Service Centre to reduce driving time for the father, however, this does not reduce the travel time for the children and causes ongoing and regular contact between the mother and father, something Ms P strongly recommended should be avoided for the mother’s mental health.
The positives of U School include the capacity for substantial involvement of both parents in the daily schooling of the children, the capacity for both parents to attend assemblies, parent teacher interviews and extracurricular events and to be actively involved in all aspects of the children’s primary education. Any contact between Mr G and the father would be minimised by the children attending different schools. The children attending U School removes the need for regular face-to-face handovers between the parents.
The negatives of U School include that each day the children will have a commute to and from school for between approximately 45 minutes (from the mother’s home) to 1 hour and 10 minutes (from the father’s home); they will likely have less connection with the local school community in both Suburb AA and Suburb B; there may be more complex logistical issues for the mother in managing her work commitments with school drop-off and pick-up (even if the children catch a school bus from Town ZZ); and there will be the competing logistics of Mr G’s children and their school attendance.

Conclusion on which school the children should attend

I have carefully considered Dr N’s opinion as to the midpoint school being a “lose-lose” option, however, I do not agree that the negative aspects of the proposal outweigh the positive aspects, the most significant of which is that it will ensure the benefit to the children of maintaining their connection to the father and the paternal family.
Whatever orders are made, the children will be experiencing a significant change from the current schooling arrangements in the Suburb B area. That will significantly decrease the time they spend and the relationships they have with their current school peers. This will be a big change, but one that both parents sought.
The travel time that will be required from both homes is not insignificant, but in my view, is not so burdensome as to prevent the practical implementation of these orders which will ensure these young children maintain very important relationships with both parents and their respective families.
Respectfully, I adopt the comments of Christie J in Luo & Bassett [2022] FedCFamC1F 178, citing the Full Court in Hamady & Mansour [2022] FedCFamC1A 1; (2022) FLC 94-071. Justice Christie stated at [79] that “[t]he fact that an adult might find the travel inconvenient (indeed onerous) does not mean the proposal is not reasonably practicable.”
There are many positives and many negatives to each proposal. The considerations as identified throughout these reasons are very finely balanced. Each proposal has merit and each has negative aspects. On balance, the evidence in this case weighs in favour of an ongoing and significant relationship with each parent, enabling both to be involved regularly in school, extracurricular activities, home routine, and significant time in each household while maintaining regular connection with both extended families. U School ensures the children will continue to have regular and significant exposure to their grandparents and paternal family and through them, their Country QQ culture, while still enjoying the benefits of a primary home with the mother, Mr G and his daughters. The children will maintain the benefit of time with their stepsiblings and the extended family of Mr G and have the local church community in which they are already established. In my view, these factors, on balance, outweigh the identified negative aspects, including that the children will continue to have to commute some way to and from school and may have less opportunity for local extracurricular activities.

WHAT THE CONFIGURATION OF THE SCHOOL HOLIDAY REGIME SHOULD BE

Competing school holiday orders

There were two issues in dispute between the parents about school holidays. The first was when the holidays should commence and end. The mother sought commencement the day after the school term ends, and the conclusion the day prior to the resumption of term. The father sought the time commence from the last day of school until the resumption of school. The second issue was whether, for the 2026 to 2027 long school holidays, the time should be week about, rather than the 14-day blocks which both parents sought after that time.
I prefer the orders sought by the father in respect of the commencement and conclusion of the school holiday time, such that the time will commence from the last day that they are obliged to attend school and ends the first day they return to school. This reduces the necessity for additional face-to-face changeovers and adds an extra couple of nights onto the holiday period, giving the children and the parties the benefit of a greater number of clear nights.
Given the young ages of the children and that the children have not had longer block periods of time away from their mother, the mother sought that for the first period of long school holiday time, the children have a week about arrangement which then becomes a fortnight about arrangement from the 2027 to 2028 long school holidays. Dr N in oral evidence supported such an arrangement.
Given the young ages of the children and that they will be adjusting to longer block periods away from their mother, it is appropriate to make the orders sought by the mother, that for the 2026 to 2027 long school holidays the children spend time in a week about arrangement and thereafter fortnightly blocks.

WHETHER THERE SHOULD BE A MUTUAL FIRST OPTION TO CARE IF THE PARENT (AND THEIR PARTNER IF APPLICABLE) IS UNABLE TO CARE FOR LONGER THAN 48 HOURS

First Option order sought by the father

I decline to make the order sought by the father for there to be a mutual order for first care if either parent, and their current or future partners, are unable to care for the children during school holiday periods for longer than 48 hours. There was no evidence or opinion from Dr N in relation to the benefit of such an order, and in such a high conflict matter, the potential for more conflict arising is, in my view, likely and should be avoided. Additionally, each parent is responsible and has the capacity to make proper arrangements for the children if they are unable to care for the children during their time in school holidays.

WHETHER OVERSEAS TRAVEL SHOULD BE PERMITTED IMMEDIATELY OR ONLY AFTER 2027

The mother opposed overseas travel commencing until the 2027 to 2028 Christmas holiday period because of the young ages of the children and her desire for them to settle into the new care arrangement and the new school.
The father sought that overseas travel be permitted to commence immediately.
The issue of whether overseas travel should be delayed was not raised with Dr N and there was no evidence as to the relevance of their age and schooling to deferring such a decision. There was no evidence that either parent had plans to travel imminently.
These children are in the fortunate position where they may be able to travel overseas during school holiday periods. The father’s cultural background is Country QQ and he has extended family in Country RR. His parents who have a close relationship with the children both gave evidence of their desire to share cultural knowledge with the children. They are elderly and I infer there may be limited opportunity for travel in the longer term with the paternal grandparents. The mother’s cultural background is Country TT. During cross-examination, it was suggested to the father that the mother may wish to take the children to Country TT.
There is no reason apparent to me to restrain either parent from exposing the children to such opportunities, and accordingly, overseas travel will be permitted during periods of time that the children are in their respective care, commencing immediately, provided that the travelling parent provides appropriate details of the proposed travel with the other parent.
In her final minute of orders sought, the mother sought an order that the parents must provide six months’ notice of intended overseas travel. This requirement is unnecessarily onerous. There was no submission made in support of the order. I decline to make the order.

ANCILLARY MATTERS

Terms of restraint and reasons

The parties agreed in principle that the mother should be restrained from relocating the children’s residence further away or from increasing the travel distance. The form of order sought by the father refers to a restraint from the father’s residence but does not contemplate that he might move residence. To ensure certainty in respect of the restraint, I will order the mother is restrained from moving further away than Suburb AA and that she is restrained from moving to a location that would increase the present distance by road to the father’s current residence without his express written consent.
I prefer the father’s orders for Mother’s Day and Father’s Day because it maintains the drop-off and collection directly from school, rather than the mother’s proposal which sought there be a handover at 4.30 pm on the Friday. The school collection and return minimises the children’s exposure to interactions between the parents.
Both parties sought time over Easter if it fell outside of school holidays time, which will avoid potential conflict, uncertainty for the children and interruption of block holiday times. The mother sought that time during Easter should commence at 4.30 pm and conclude at 7.30 am and the father sought the time commence from after school, with a mid-point swap over at 3.00 pm, and conclude at 9.00 am at school.
The father’s proposed orders avoid the parties having a direct handover at the commencement and conclusion of time which avoids the children being exposed to interactions and tensions between the parties and also avoids exposing the mother to direct contact with the father as recommended by Ms P in her 7 October 2024 report, in circumstances where she opined the father is “so triggering to [the mother]”. Dr N also opined that it is important to protect children from exposure to further high conflict and instability. For these reasons, the father’s orders which avoid direct contact between the parties in front of the children are preferred as orders that are in the best interests of the children.

Mother’s application for parents to continue to attend current mental health treaters

The mother sought in her final minute of orders that the parties shall do all things to continue to attend their current mental health treaters at such intervals and for as long as recommended by the treater.
There was no submission made in support of such an order.
The parents each indicated their intention to continue to work with their trusted mental health practitioners. I have no reason to doubt that they will do so. However, such an order is not a parenting order as it is a self-standing order and not tethered, nor is it a condition of time to be spent with the children.
As identified by the Full Court in Oberlin & Infeld [2021] FamCAFC 66; (2021) FLC 94-017 and Lainhart & Ellinson [2023] FedCFamC1A 200; (2023) FLC 94-166, the proposed order is not a parenting order, and I decline to make it.

CONCLUSION ON PARENTING ORDERS

I am satisfied that the orders made herein are in the best interests of the children.
